Credit to gabriellehopemusic</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/YSKiJh4</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[ewakemanVA]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>You are in heaven</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/w6oVwbZ</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/eDeDnlG.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/w6oVwbZ</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[carambolage]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Google the lyrics...</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/AVYprS0</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/Yy0yhhZ.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>In 1972, Italian singer Adriano Celentano released “Prisencolinensinainciusol,” a song with nonsense lyrics meant to sound like English. The idea was to see if Italians would like any song that sounded American, regardless of the lyrics’ meaning. It became a huge hit in Italy and across Europe, reaching number one in Italy and charting in other countries like the UK. The song mixed funk, soul, and early hip-hop, with Celentano improvising gibberish lyrics over a catchy beat. His performances on TV helped spread its popularity, and the song became a cultural meme decades later, reflecting the era’s love for American music.</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/AVYprS0</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[BenntheNinja]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>9 years of remission</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/HO1WIFw</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/rs6k9LA.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>9 years and 35lb of muscle later, I’m feeling good after spending months in the hospital with Crohn’s disease.</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/HO1WIFw</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Squatch9883]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Meme City #2099</title><lin